{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.07,0.02,0.03,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90309"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1711"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74563"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30971"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90309"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is being assessed after an episode of right upper quadrant pain. The pain lasted about two hours and has now resolved. She has had two similar episodes in the last month. She is otherwise in good health and does not take any medications. She is a non-smoker and drinks about two glasses of wine at weekends. She does not take any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable. An ultrasound confirms the presence of gallstones. She is counselled to undergo a laparoscopic cholecystectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most suggestive that an ERCP should be undertaken prior to the cholecystectomy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stones in the common bile duct","Deranged liver function tests","Small stones within the gallbladder","A thick-walled gallbladder","A common bile duct diameter of 8mm (usual \u003C6mm)"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the assessment of any patient with symptomatic gallstones, consideration must always be given to the chances of finding stones in the common bile duct (CBD), which occurs in 10-20% of patients. If \u003Cstrong\u003Estones in the common bile duct\u003C/strong\u003E are identified on US, then further imaging is not usually required and these patients should proceed to ERCP pre-operatively for stone extraction or laparoscopic cholecystectomy with bile duct exploration (if surgical expertise permits). Studies have found these approaches to be equally valid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients who have \u003Cstrong\u003Ederanged liver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E (LFTs) with normal calibre biliary system, or \u003Cstrong\u003ECBD dilation\u003C/strong\u003E with normal LFTs should either have further imaging with MRCP, or proceed to laparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative cholangiogram (IOC) for ductal imaging. Some moderate elevation of all serum liver enzymes can occur after episodes of biliary colic or acute cholecystitis. The finding of a common bile duct greater than 7mm might increase the probability of a stone in the duct - but this diameter can still be a normal finding in many individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethick-walled gallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E would be more in-keeping with cholecystitis and indication for laparoscopic cholecystectomy in the first instance. Certainly \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall stones within the gallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E can more easily pass through the cystic duct into the common bile duct, but size alone should not determine the risk. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["10-20% of symptomatic patients with gallstones have common bile duct stones"],"references":["Williams E, Beckingham I, Sayed GE, Gurusamy K, Sturgess R, Webster G, Young T. Updated guideline on the management of common bile duct stones (CBDS). Gut 2017; 66: 765-82."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74563"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74563"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T17:21:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T17:21:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1711"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90309"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi